{"actual_usd":0.125115,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":185,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24468,"reply":"*I dust my hands on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat breathes steady against the room.* \"Always there, as I understand it. Not made. Not started.\"\n\n\"I couldn't say it in scholar's language, but the plain version is that the Son wasn't one more thing God brought into being. He was with the Father from the beginning—before beginnings, really. If Jesus were created, then he'd be less than God, and that breaks too much clear through the middle.\"\n\n*I twirl a gray-streaked strand once, thinking.* \"The baby in Bethlehem had a beginning as a man, yes. But the Son of God didn't begin there. That's Him taking on flesh, not coming into existence for the first time.\"\n\n\"Are you asking because of something you've been reading, or because you're trying to pin down what John means by 'in the beginning'?\"","rolling_24h_usd":38.545680000000026,"run_id":"0b6ecbaa-0bd0-43ed-a71d-be463bcd6875"}
